{
  "text": "Remark 1.5. Note that the case when p = q = 1 is not covered. This is the case when neither one of the exponents of the ensemble grows to \u221e; the method of proof collapses since one of the main ingredients, the ability to get uniform tail bounds for entries of the matrix is no longer true at the \"bottom right\" corner of the matrix, and as such the errors can no longer be accurately estimated by the same means. We present the results of some numerical simulations for this case in Section 6. We also note that the theorem is proven by Johansson in the \u03b2 = 2 case by methods of orthogonal polynomial theory [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "121136569"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "121136569": {
      "title": "On random matrices from the compact classical groups",
      "abstract": "If M is a matrix taken randomly with respect to normalized Haar measure on U(n), O(n) or Sp(n), then the real and imaginary parts of the random variables Tr(Mk), k > 1, converge to independent normal random variables with mean zero and variance k/2, as the size n of the matrix goes to infinity. For the unitary group this is a direct consequence of the strong Szeg6 theorem for Toeplitz determinants. We will prove a conjecture of Diaconis"
    }
  }
}